,Recommended,304410,21370805,"Posted: 21 February, 2016",all,Holocene - Moving House,"Hexcells Infinite, like the other hexcell games, still follows the same gameplay. Basically a mix of minesweeper and sudoku. The game has nice background music like the others and this particular game has an added feature where you can play custom puzzles.However, where this game fails for me is it’s made the same mistake as hexcells plus. While the original hexcells had a nice difficulty curve, this one's all over the place. I actually enjoyed playing the first hour and I thought they'd redeemed themselves from hexcells plus. I was getting stuck, but still progressing which makes the game fun. But the levels difficulties are all over the place. For example one level introduced a new concept and gave you an incredibly easy puzzle to make sure you understand it. Then just the level after it throws you into this massive puzzle with numbers all over the place and I'm just sitting there thinking, I can't be bothered with this. It becomes more of a grind and loses its fun. I think it would have been nice for the dev to add a mid-level save so you can come back later; some of these levels are massive and will take a long time.I'm also very disappointed that they added a ? cell. It's so cheap because it forces you to solve the puzzle in only one possible way. It can also be so disheartening; you might spend a solid 5 minutes to find a cell you can make progress on only to uncover it as a ? so you can no longer progress any further down that route.However, do I think this game is worth buying? Yes! Solely because you can play custom levels. It offers more than the other hexcells games. So, although there are some things wrong with this game I can still say it's worth buying."
76561198024985610,Recommended,304410,32207416,Posted: 5 June,all,Ryuuga Hideki,"This game is a perfect stress reliever for me. The music is blissfully serene, and the puzzles are both enjoyable and almost entirely logical with very few blind guesses involved.Gameplay wise it's largely Minesweeper based infused with a dash of Picross-style logic. It may seem a little daunting at first but the rules are explained very well and it quickly becomes second nature.If you like logic puzzles then you can't go wrong with this game, especially for the price. While there aren't technically an infinite number of puzzles (and the generated puzzles will occasionally feel same-y due to using the same logic patterns) there are more puzzles here than you could possibly play in a lifetime."
,Recommended,304410,13233535,"Posted: 4 December, 2014",all,Babies#11425,"This series is criminally overlooked.If you enjoy games like sudoku, you will find logical puzzles here that work your brain for hours. While a naive comparison, the game plays similarly to a very advanced Minesweeper. By the second act, though, you'll have discovered the futility of that comparison; this game is on an entirely different level and has an elegance in the solutions that random Minesweeper puzzles cannot ever hope to achieve.A couple of the puzzles stumped me for more than 90 minutes, and my roommate rapidly grew tired of me talking the solution out loud as I moved my mouse around. There's a brilliant simplicity to the gameplay and yet, while playing, one must keep a large amount of logic in their head. It's easy to get overwhelmed by logic in one area of the puzzle while overlooking the simple move forward in another area, and the feeling is intense when you slap your forehead in stupidity on discovering it.The soundtrack is quite relaxing, and even after working on the same puzzle for an hour it did not grow tiresome. It's really fun when you get on a ""roll"" of solving the puzzle, too, because you generate little ditties as a reward.The only negative of Infinite compared to the rest of the series is the randomly-generated puzzles. The developer added these so that he could put a bow on the series and call it done and, while they do indeed fill a gap, you can tell they're a far different experience than the handmade puzzles (don't worry, Infinite has the same number of handmade puzzles as the previous two). Sudoku has this issue, too, and it's just the nature of puzzle generation algorithms. Still, if you're dying for a new puzzle, they might hold you over, otherwise I'd just play them for the achievement.At any rate, I've found if I step away from a puzzle or play others, I forget a solution, so you could probably revisit the entire series in a few weeks' time and have a whole new game.The entire Hexcells series contains puzzles that are among the greatest I've ever solved. I highly recommend the entire collection, and also very strongly recommend that you start with Hexcells. It is easier than the other two, this one included, by far. Definitely, though, work up to this one. Absolutely worth your purchase.For perspective, I am not the greatest logician, and I invested about 13 hours solving this campaign -- for 13 hours of gameplay, this game is a steal."
