76561198150891487,Not Recommended,304410,31869620,Posted: 20 May,all,Wheat Snuffles,"Before I start this review, I wanted to recommend ""Tetrobot and Co."" to those who look for intellectual challenges. It's a far superior puzzle game than the Hexcells trilogy, and is a game that actually challenges your problem solving skills.Now onto Hexcells Infinite.The idea of different types of hints comparing to minesweeper is refreshing, there are 3 types of additional hints besides the number of adjacent blue hexes:1) Number of blue hexes in a column2) Consecutive or non-consecutive blue hexes in adjacent hexes/column3) Number of blue hexes in 2 hex radiusHowever the freshness of new ideas runs out extremely quickly, and there will be no more new mechanics from that point on - the game becomes extremely repetitive, with few exceptions.There are 2 methods the developer adopts to make this game challenging:1) Reduce redundant information to bare minimum, by giving you non-blue hexes with question mark instead of an actual number. In my eyes, all this does is to make the levels long, and extremely unsatisfying to solve. It doesn't really pose interesting challenges, instead it just creates dead ends and forces you to move to somewhere else. When you have a board with over 400 hexes, it gets extremely annoying and frustrating to click on that one non-blue hex only to see a question mark.2) Create extremely large levels that take over half an hour to complete (if your goal is to make 0 mistakes) - or significantly longer if you are not a fast thinker. Many levels include completely independent sections which would have served much better as multiple smaller levels. Instead of keep creating interesting mechanics, the only variation becomes the overall shape of each level. It's quite sad to see a promising idea dying so quickly, it's like a novel with amazing first 3 chapters, but 20 more boring and mundane long chapters after, ruining the entire book.The way this game works, is for the player to slowly exhaust all the available information to determine which ones are blue hexes. But because there are only 4 types of information, it really doesn't require that much problem solving skills or creativity. Most later campaign levels feel like chores, and you are forced to do them slowly. At some point you might be forced to take a guess, and seeing the 0 mistake jumping to 1, ruining your perfect record, is quite infuriating.The game has nice audio, however there are some minor technical issues:1) Regardless of which monitor is selected to play the game in windowed mode, the game would always launch across all monitors. If the developer wanted to, this bug can be easily fixed in minutes.2) If you click really quickly, sometimes clicks won't register.In conclusion, I wouldn't recommend this game to any of my friends."
