,Recommended,304410,21546194,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,Mordamir,"In a nutshell: Hexcells Infinite is Minesweeper on steroids.Long story: Just like in Minesweeper, sometimes you’ll have to guess (which may or may not annoy you), but unlike Minesweeper, Hexcells allows you to make as many mistakes as necessary in order to complete a map, and THAT is my major beef with the game, because it detracted a lot from the challenge. That’s right: There is no *significant* reward for completing a map with zero mistakes, and there is no punishment for literally guessing every step of the way and finishing with 20+ mistakes (other than barring your progress through the blocks of preset levels, but unlocking all puzzle groups doesn't really pose much of a challenge, i.e. you can do that even if you finish each map with a few mistakes).On the bright side, extra points go to sound design, as every correct click results in a soothing, oddly satisfying sound bit; however, there is no volume control in the game, only an ON/OFF switch, which I suppose is aligned with the game’s minimalistic design, but it’s a feature I missed nonetheless.All in all, the game is reasonably priced, and certainly a step up the challenge of playing Minesweeper. If you’re looking for some casual distraction of the “minesweeping” variety, I’d say go for it."
