76561198110595954,Recommended,304410,34092421,Posted: 7 August,all,RagnCharran,"Hexcells Infinite is a great little puzzle game that also fixes a few of the issues of the earlier games in the series, HexCells and HexCells Plus (both of which I also fully recommend, despite their minor flaws). This game has both premade puzzles, on a fair learning curve of difficulty, and a procedural generation system that presumably is capable of generating an additional 100,000,000 different puzzles. This solves the replay issue of the previous games, and also includes a save feature (letting you leave a puzzle and come back without having to start over), and the option to swap your mouse buttons (which is critical if you're a Minesweeper player as the default ""safe"" or ""flag"" buttons are opposite). And just as HexCells Plus increased the size and complexity of puzzles compared to HexCells, HexCells Infinite increases them even more, so that save function is a lifesaver on the later puzzles.And yes, this is a Minsweeper style puzzle game, but because the levels are premade they progress on a fair learning curve and are all 100% logic solvable with no guessing required, ever. At the risk of sounding condescending, if you're reading a negative review by someone who says guessing is required, they just couldn't logic the puzzle out. I was able to logic solve them all, and when I did make an error, I was able to figure out what error in logic I had made, or what I had failed to notice, that caused my mistake. The game lets you make a few mistakes without failing you on the level, but as a perfectionist I restarted from scratch each time, and was able to clear them all.Even the procedurally generated ""Infinite"" levels seem to follow the 100% solvable rule, I've done about 20 so far and had no problems, and in each I could see what are probably the base elements of coding that ensure the levels are solvable. There are often multiple - or as I see it, overlapping - ways to prove many of the cells as safe or not, which I'm guessing comes from the failsafe coding. The downside to this is they tend to be fairly easy, even the really large puzzles (the generator makes them in multiple sizes as well as configurations) have none of the complex logic required to beat the higher premade levels.The only downsides I see are:1. Because this is a standalone game, it has tutorial style puzzles to teach the mechanics of the various logic rules, but if you're already familiar with the series you'll solve them almost instantly.2. There's still no ""maybe"" flag, so any ""what if"" analysis you do has to be in your head or on paper, and with the complexity of some of the puzzles, this is an ever bigger problem here than it was in the earlier games int he series.Fully recommend."
,Recommended,304410,34105260,Posted: 8 August,all,沒有坦克的砲台,"The level generating algorithm really adds a lot of replayability to the game, even though the generated levels are mostly much easier than latter normal levels."
